1
00:00:22,732 --> 00:00:25,484
(WATER FLOWING)

2
00:00:31,991 --> 00:00:33,910
(DEVICE CRACKLING)

3
00:00:35,369 --> 00:00:38,039
(PANTING)

4
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:42,960
(CRANK FLASHLIGHT WHIRRING)

5
00:00:48,341 --> 00:00:49,967
(CRANK FLASHLIGHT WHIRRING)

6
00:01:01,604 --> 00:01:03,356
(MAN GASPS)

7
00:01:08,361 --> 00:01:09,737
(CRACKLING CONTINUES)

8
00:01:33,469 --> 00:01:35,721
(DEVICE CONTINUES CRACKLING)

9
00:02:19,056 --> 00:02:20,683
- (HELICOPTER BLADES WHIRRING)
- (SIGHS)

10
00:02:21,892 --> 00:02:24,770
Is it possible that the water
has already killed them?

11
00:02:25,187 --> 00:02:27,148
Yes.

12
00:02:27,231 --> 00:02:28,774
Then what?

13
00:02:29,984 --> 00:02:31,777
If it doesn't work?

14
00:02:37,700 --> 00:02:39,994
(HELICOPTER APPROACHING)

15
00:02:49,462 --> 00:02:51,881
(DEVICE CRACKLING)

16
00:03:03,517 --> 00:03:05,770
(MUFFLED CONVERSATION)

17
00:03:37,760 --> 00:03:39,678
(BANGING ON DOOR)

18
00:03:44,642 --> 00:03:45,893
(PANTING)

19
00:03:48,187 --> 00:03:50,523
(APPLAUSE)

20
00:04:04,662 --> 00:04:06,163
Get them in the truck.

21
00:04:07,123 --> 00:04:09,250
Get the hoses in! Start pumping!

22
00:04:25,724 --> 00:04:28,644
Uh, I'm here to see
my husband, Vasily Ignatenko.

23
00:04:28,727 --> 00:04:31,188
He's a firefighter from Chernobyl.
I have permission.

24
00:04:31,397 --> 00:04:33,774
Chernobyl? I'm sorry, no visitors.

25
00:04:36,068 --> 00:04:38,487
Well, but Major...
Major Burov told me,

26
00:04:38,571 --> 00:04:39,905
- he said...
- No exceptions.

27
00:04:39,989 --> 00:04:42,783
Please. I've come all the way
from Kievskaya Oblast.

28
00:05:03,179 --> 00:05:04,305
(STAMPS FORM)

29
00:05:08,893 --> 00:05:10,603
Excuse me.

30
00:05:11,937 --> 00:05:13,397
Excuse me, excuse me.

31
00:05:13,481 --> 00:05:14,773
Who are you? What are you doing here?

32
00:05:14,857 --> 00:05:17,651
- I have a pass.
- You can't be here. It's not safe.

33
00:05:17,735 --> 00:05:19,612
I am here to see my husband.

34
00:05:19,695 --> 00:05:20,696
Vasily Ignatenko.

35
00:05:20,779 --> 00:05:22,281
He's a firefighter from Chernobyl.

36
00:05:22,364 --> 00:05:24,825
I know who Ignatenko is,
but you can't.

37
00:05:24,909 --> 00:05:26,911
I have permission. I've...

38
00:05:33,209 --> 00:05:36,587
You can see him for 30 minutes,
not a minute more.

39
00:05:36,670 --> 00:05:39,465
And you cannot touch him in any way.
Do you understand?

40
00:05:39,548 --> 00:05:41,800
- Yeah.
- Room 15.

41
00:05:43,552 --> 00:05:44,553
Thank you.

42
00:05:45,179 --> 00:05:47,056
- You're not pregnant, are you?
- No.

43
00:05:54,980 --> 00:05:56,649
VASILY: I won't have
to give that to you.

44
00:05:56,732 --> 00:05:57,775
MAN: There they are.

45
00:05:58,192 --> 00:05:59,777
No, wait, wait, wait.
I haven't finished yet.

46
00:05:59,860 --> 00:06:00,986
PRAVIK: No, no, he hasn't.

47
00:06:01,779 --> 00:06:03,113
Yeah, that's good.

48
00:06:05,991 --> 00:06:07,243
Yeah, better.

49
00:06:10,162 --> 00:06:11,872
Look who the cat dragged in.

50
00:06:14,500 --> 00:06:16,168
VASILY: What did I tell you?

51
00:06:17,002 --> 00:06:19,338
There's no hiding from you,
is there? Eh?

52
00:06:20,923 --> 00:06:21,924
(GROANS)

53
00:06:22,675 --> 00:06:24,677
Easy, easy. It's okay.

54
00:06:24,760 --> 00:06:28,055
We're all okay. Yeah, we're okay.

55
00:06:38,816 --> 00:06:40,067
(INAUDIBLE)

56
00:06:50,703 --> 00:06:52,788
(HELICOPTER BLADES WHIRRING)

57
00:06:58,377 --> 00:07:00,045
(DEVICE CRACKLING)

58
00:07:38,042 --> 00:07:41,545
How, how, how did this happen?
Who gave them the idea?

59
00:07:41,629 --> 00:07:43,505
- Are you suggesting I did?
- Someone did.

60
00:07:43,589 --> 00:07:47,092
Someone decided
that the evacuation zone

61
00:07:47,176 --> 00:07:50,346
should be 30 kilometers,
when we know, here,

62
00:07:50,429 --> 00:07:53,182
cesium-137 in the Gomel district.

63
00:07:53,265 --> 00:07:55,893
- That's 200 kilometers away!
- It was decided.

64
00:07:55,976 --> 00:07:57,895
- Based on what?
- I don't know!

65
00:07:59,355 --> 00:08:03,275
Forgive me. Maybe I... I've just
spent too much time in my lab.

66
00:08:03,359 --> 00:08:05,027
Or maybe I'm just stupid.

67
00:08:05,819 --> 00:08:07,571
Is this really the way it all works?

68
00:08:08,697 --> 00:08:10,574
An uninformed, arbitrary decision

69
00:08:10,658 --> 00:08:12,910
that will cost who knows
how many lives

70
00:08:12,993 --> 00:08:16,872
made by some apparatchik?
Some career party man?

71
00:08:18,957 --> 00:08:21,043
I'm a career party man.

72
00:08:22,002 --> 00:08:24,797
You should watch your tone,
Comrade Legasov.

73
00:08:25,923 --> 00:08:27,091
PIKALOV: Comrades...

74
00:08:28,133 --> 00:08:30,803
We have visual confirmation
that the fire is nearly extinguished.

75
00:08:30,886 --> 00:08:32,888
There has also been
a reduction in iodine-131

76
00:08:32,971 --> 00:08:34,807
and cesium-137 emissions.

77
00:08:34,890 --> 00:08:36,517
Good. Yes?

78
00:08:37,309 --> 00:08:40,145
But the temperature is rising.

79
00:08:40,229 --> 00:08:41,605
And, uh...

80
00:08:48,779 --> 00:08:51,657
LEGASOV: There's a spike
in zirconium-95.

81
00:08:52,991 --> 00:08:56,203
It's from the cladding
on the fuel rods.

82
00:08:56,286 --> 00:08:58,622
SHCHERBINA: Meaning what?

83
00:08:58,706 --> 00:09:01,083
The meltdown has begun.

84
00:09:30,946 --> 00:09:33,157
(INDISTINCT MOANING IN DISTANCE)

85
00:09:39,705 --> 00:09:41,248
VASILY: Get it off me!

86
00:09:43,876 --> 00:09:46,253
Get it off me!

87
00:09:48,380 --> 00:09:50,215
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)

88
00:09:53,761 --> 00:09:55,262
DR. VETROVA: Stop moving!

89
00:09:55,345 --> 00:09:58,098
- Get off him! You're hurting him!
- (SOBBING)

90
00:09:58,932 --> 00:10:01,059
- DOCTOR: You can't be in here.
- What's happening to him?

91
00:10:01,143 --> 00:10:02,603
Get out!

92
00:10:02,686 --> 00:10:04,438
You can't be in here!

93
00:10:04,521 --> 00:10:07,232
(VASILY WAILING)

94
00:10:11,361 --> 00:10:13,739
(SHOUTING CONTINUES)

95
00:10:44,937 --> 00:10:46,021
(PHONE RINGS)

96
00:10:47,397 --> 00:10:48,398
Yes?

97
00:10:48,482 --> 00:10:49,983
MAN ON PHONE: Comrade Shcherbina
is on the phone.

98
00:10:50,067 --> 00:10:51,443
Put him through.

99
00:10:52,903 --> 00:10:54,196
Well?

100
00:10:54,279 --> 00:10:55,948
SHCHERBINA: The fire's nearly out.

101
00:10:56,031 --> 00:10:57,783
The bubbler tanks are being drained.

102
00:10:57,866 --> 00:11:00,828
We have successfully eliminated
the risk of a thermal explosion.

103
00:11:01,787 --> 00:11:03,956
(INHALES DEEPLY)

104
00:11:04,039 --> 00:11:05,040
And?

105
00:11:06,542 --> 00:11:08,168
The situation inside the core

106
00:11:08,252 --> 00:11:11,129
is deteriorating
faster than anticipated.

107
00:11:11,213 --> 00:11:14,091
The concrete pad will last
for six to eight weeks,

108
00:11:14,174 --> 00:11:17,219
but after that, Legasov estimates
a 50% chance

109
00:11:17,302 --> 00:11:19,012
that the fuel will breach the pad

110
00:11:19,096 --> 00:11:21,807
and melt down
into the groundwater itself.

111
00:11:22,766 --> 00:11:25,310
(STAMMERS) And where
does this groundwater go?

112
00:11:25,394 --> 00:11:27,437
The Pripyat River,

113
00:11:27,521 --> 00:11:30,440
which feeds into the Dnieper.

114
00:11:30,524 --> 00:11:33,902
The primary water supply for
approximately 50 million people,

115
00:11:33,986 --> 00:11:38,115
not to mention crops and livestock,
would be unusable.

116
00:11:38,198 --> 00:11:40,909
We're recommending we install
a heat exchanger under the pad

117
00:11:40,993 --> 00:11:44,079
to lower the core temperature
and halt the meltdown.

118
00:11:44,162 --> 00:11:47,207
And in order to do that,
I'm told that we will need

119
00:11:49,543 --> 00:11:53,380
all of the liquid nitrogen
in the Soviet Union.

120
00:11:55,841 --> 00:11:56,842
Oh.

121
00:11:58,010 --> 00:11:59,094
All right.

122
00:11:59,177 --> 00:12:00,762
SHCHERBINA: Yeah, and of course,
we'll also need...

123
00:12:00,846 --> 00:12:02,139
Whatever you need, you have it.

124
00:12:02,222 --> 00:12:03,640
- That should be clear by now.
- Yes.

125
00:12:03,724 --> 00:12:05,309
- Anything else?
- Uh, no, no, no. Thank you.

126
00:12:05,392 --> 00:12:08,437
Yes. I'd like to address
the 30-kilometer exclusion zone.

127
00:12:08,520 --> 00:12:11,273
Wait, what?
Professor Legasov, is that you?

128
00:12:11,356 --> 00:12:12,608
What exclusion zone?

129
00:12:12,691 --> 00:12:14,735
Minor details, General Secretary.

130
00:12:14,818 --> 00:12:17,362
Um, Premier Ryzhkov
has determined that...

131
00:12:17,446 --> 00:12:19,823
If he determined, then he determined.

132
00:12:19,907 --> 00:12:21,325
Look, Professor Legasov,

133
00:12:21,408 --> 00:12:23,327
you are there for one reason only.

134
00:12:23,410 --> 00:12:25,454
Do you understand? To make this stop.

135
00:12:25,537 --> 00:12:26,747
I don't want questions.

136
00:12:26,830 --> 00:12:28,457
I want to know when this will be over.

137
00:12:28,832 --> 00:12:30,876
If you mean when will
Chernobyl be completely safe,

138
00:12:30,959 --> 00:12:34,129
the half-life of plutonium-239
is 24,000 years.

139
00:12:34,212 --> 00:12:37,382
So perhaps we should just say,
"Not within our lifetimes."

140
00:12:39,092 --> 00:12:40,552
(LINE DISCONNECTS)

141
00:12:49,645 --> 00:12:51,521
I think you and I should take a walk.

142
00:12:52,064 --> 00:12:53,732
It's late. I'm tired.

143
00:12:54,816 --> 00:12:57,152
We're taking a walk.

144
00:13:03,617 --> 00:13:06,036
What is it you want? An apology?

145
00:13:07,829 --> 00:13:09,539
Not gonna sit back and...

146
00:13:10,332 --> 00:13:11,375
(LEGASOV SIGHS)

147
00:13:11,458 --> 00:13:13,543
What will happen to our boys?

148
00:13:14,461 --> 00:13:16,880
Which boys? The divers?

149
00:13:16,964 --> 00:13:19,883
The divers, the firefighters,
the men in the control room.

150
00:13:20,592 --> 00:13:23,971
What does the radiation
do to them, precisely?

151
00:13:25,681 --> 00:13:28,308
At the levels
some of them were exposed?

152
00:13:28,392 --> 00:13:31,520
Ionizing radiation tears
the cellular structure apart.

153
00:13:32,479 --> 00:13:35,315
The skin blisters,
turns red, then black.

154
00:13:36,984 --> 00:13:39,486
This is followed by a latency period.

155
00:13:40,696 --> 00:13:42,572
The immediate effects subside.

156
00:13:42,656 --> 00:13:44,408
The patient appears to be recovering.

157
00:13:45,617 --> 00:13:47,995
Healthy, even. But they aren't.

158
00:13:49,621 --> 00:13:52,958
This usually only lasts
for a day or two.

159
00:13:55,460 --> 00:13:56,670
Continue.

160
00:13:58,213 --> 00:14:01,925
Then the cellular damage
begins to manifest.

161
00:14:02,009 --> 00:14:07,389
The bone marrow dies,
the immune system fails,

162
00:14:07,472 --> 00:14:11,184
the organs and soft tissue
begin to decompose.

163
00:14:11,268 --> 00:14:15,313
The arteries and veins
spill open like sieves,

164
00:14:15,397 --> 00:14:17,816
to the point where you can't
even administer morphine

165
00:14:17,899 --> 00:14:21,486
for the pain, which is unimaginable.

166
00:14:22,279 --> 00:14:25,532
And then three days
to three weeks, you're dead.

167
00:14:27,784 --> 00:14:30,037
That is what will happen
to those boys.

168
00:14:32,372 --> 00:14:33,749
And what about us?

169
00:14:37,169 --> 00:14:38,962
Well, we've...

170
00:14:39,046 --> 00:14:42,007
We've gotten a steady dose,
but not as much of it.

171
00:14:43,341 --> 00:14:45,177
Not strong enough to kill the cells,

172
00:14:45,260 --> 00:14:48,305
but consistent enough
to damage our DNA.

173
00:14:49,765 --> 00:14:52,517
So, in time, cancer.

174
00:14:53,060 --> 00:14:56,313
Or aplastic anemia. Either way, fatal.

175
00:14:59,066 --> 00:15:00,358
Well...

176
00:15:02,402 --> 00:15:08,033
In a sense, it would seem we've
gotten off easy then, Valery.

177
00:15:20,712 --> 00:15:22,506
I've seen them before.

178
00:15:28,553 --> 00:15:31,848
SHCHERBINA: Now you know
why I wanted to take a walk.

179
00:15:31,932 --> 00:15:34,184
We can presume
the work site is bugged.

180
00:15:35,185 --> 00:15:39,231
And our rooms, even our bathrooms.

181
00:15:39,314 --> 00:15:41,483
They've been here the whole time.

182
00:15:41,566 --> 00:15:43,568
Of course, they've been here
the whole time.

183
00:15:44,820 --> 00:15:48,698
But if we're seeing them
out in the open now,

184
00:15:48,782 --> 00:15:51,451
it's because they want us to know.

185
00:16:08,218 --> 00:16:09,219
(DOOR OPENS)

186
00:16:10,846 --> 00:16:11,847
(DOOR CLOSES)

187
00:16:33,326 --> 00:16:34,494
KHOMYUK: You've seen that?

188
00:16:36,955 --> 00:16:38,999
The fuel is melting
faster than we expected.

189
00:16:39,082 --> 00:16:41,376
I know. I have a plan.

190
00:16:42,127 --> 00:16:44,713
Heat exchanger, I hope.

191
00:16:44,796 --> 00:16:46,256
Yes.

192
00:16:49,467 --> 00:16:51,386
There's something I've wanted
to ask you, comrade,

193
00:16:51,469 --> 00:16:54,848
but I see you're already asking
yourself the same question.

194
00:16:58,602 --> 00:17:00,854
Why did it explode?

195
00:17:02,564 --> 00:17:04,858
I've worked the numbers over and over,

196
00:17:04,941 --> 00:17:08,528
presuming the worst possible
conditions in an RBMK reactor.

197
00:17:10,530 --> 00:17:13,158
And I always get the same answer.

198
00:17:13,241 --> 00:17:14,659
Which is?

199
00:17:16,077 --> 00:17:17,245
It's not possible.

200
00:17:18,455 --> 00:17:19,873
And yet...

201
00:17:22,959 --> 00:17:25,045
You're not going to solve this here.

202
00:17:26,713 --> 00:17:28,215
Not on paper.

203
00:17:29,925 --> 00:17:31,718
Everyone who was in the control room,

204
00:17:31,801 --> 00:17:34,179
Dyatlov, Akimov, Toptunov,

205
00:17:34,262 --> 00:17:37,766
they're all in Moscow,
Hospital Number 6.

206
00:17:38,683 --> 00:17:41,728
We need to find out exactly
what happened that night,

207
00:17:41,811 --> 00:17:45,273
moment by moment,
decision by decision.

208
00:17:46,691 --> 00:17:48,693
Go now while they're still alive.

209
00:17:48,777 --> 00:17:50,987
Talk to them.

210
00:17:51,071 --> 00:17:53,657
Because if we don't find out
how this happened,

211
00:17:53,740 --> 00:17:56,034
it will happen again.

212
00:17:59,246 --> 00:18:00,956
And, Khomyuk...

213
00:18:02,332 --> 00:18:03,959
Be careful.

214
00:18:11,216 --> 00:18:12,717
(ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)

215
00:18:12,801 --> 00:18:14,636
(ELEVATOR RATTLING)

216
00:18:28,525 --> 00:18:30,068
Well, fuck you!

217
00:18:30,151 --> 00:18:31,486
(LAUGHTER)

218
00:18:33,029 --> 00:18:34,990
Hey, here's one, here's one.

219
00:18:35,073 --> 00:18:36,992
What's as big as a house,

220
00:18:37,075 --> 00:18:40,120
burns 20 liters of fuel every hour,

221
00:18:40,203 --> 00:18:42,038
puts out a shit-load of smoke
and noise,

222
00:18:43,248 --> 00:18:45,500
and cuts an apple into three pieces?

223
00:18:48,044 --> 00:18:51,506
A Soviet machine made to cut
apples into four pieces!

224
00:18:51,589 --> 00:18:53,049
(LAUGHTER)

225
00:19:30,837 --> 00:19:33,298
- Who's in charge here?
- GLUKHOV: I'm the crew chief.

226
00:19:34,966 --> 00:19:38,178
I am Shadov,
Minister of Coal Industries.

227
00:19:38,261 --> 00:19:39,554
We know who you are.

228
00:19:41,765 --> 00:19:43,433
How many men do you have?

229
00:19:44,017 --> 00:19:47,520
On this shift, 45 here,
a hundred in total.

230
00:19:48,438 --> 00:19:51,399
I need all 100 men to gather
their equipment and get in the trucks.

231
00:19:52,650 --> 00:19:55,070
Do you? To where?

232
00:19:56,821 --> 00:19:58,031
That's classified.

233
00:20:04,746 --> 00:20:05,914
Come on, then.

234
00:20:06,498 --> 00:20:07,749
Start shooting.

235
00:20:08,208 --> 00:20:10,919
You haven't got enough
bullets for all of us.

236
00:20:11,002 --> 00:20:13,171
Kill as many as you can,
whoever's left,

237
00:20:13,505 --> 00:20:15,131
they'll beat the living piss
out of each of you.

238
00:20:15,215 --> 00:20:17,467
- You can't talk to us like that!
- Shut the fuck up!

239
00:20:18,635 --> 00:20:21,137
This is Tula. This is our mine.

240
00:20:22,180 --> 00:20:23,973
We don't leave unless we know why.

241
00:20:26,017 --> 00:20:27,102
Mmm.

242
00:20:31,272 --> 00:20:33,274
You're going to Chernobyl.

243
00:20:35,402 --> 00:20:36,986
Do you know what's happened there?

244
00:20:38,113 --> 00:20:40,115
We dig up coal, not bodies.

245
00:20:41,282 --> 00:20:43,576
The reactor fuel is going
to sink into the ground

246
00:20:43,660 --> 00:20:46,579
and poison the water
from Kiev to the Black Sea.

247
00:20:46,663 --> 00:20:47,997
All of it.

248
00:20:49,124 --> 00:20:50,625
Forever, they say.

249
00:20:52,752 --> 00:20:55,296
They want you
to stop that from happening.

250
00:20:56,673 --> 00:20:58,842
And how are we supposed to do that?

251
00:20:59,676 --> 00:21:02,303
They didn't tell me,
because I don't need to know.

252
00:21:04,264 --> 00:21:06,766
Do you need to know,
or have you heard enough?

253
00:21:40,633 --> 00:21:42,218
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

254
00:21:48,016 --> 00:21:50,810
Now you look like
the Minister of Coal.

255
00:22:10,205 --> 00:22:11,414
(VASILY GROANS)

256
00:22:12,373 --> 00:22:13,791
